                    <li><strong>DeFi infrastructure scenario.</strong> Wrapping depeg, oracle stale, bridge exploit. Loss = collateral, recovery near zero.</li>
                    <li><strong>0% borrowing baseline.</strong> The just-HODL anchor as a continuously visible alternative to whatever scenario you're modeling.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- TAB III: BORROW vs. SELL vs. HODL              -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- Self-contained calculator. Shares stack / price / loan / rate    -->
    <!-- with Loan Health via a JS sync layer (localStorage-backed) so    -->
    <!-- the user only enters those once. BvS-specific inputs (horizon,   -->
    <!-- cost basis, capital gains tax) live only on this tab.            -->
    <!-- Three paths compared:                                             -->
    <!--   HODL   — don't borrow, don't sell, forgo the need              -->
    <!--   BORROW — loan against stack, repay at horizon                  -->
    <!--   SELL   — crystallize BTC at today's price                       -->
    <div class="tab-content" id="tab-borrow-vs-sell">
        <div class="section-intro">
            <h2>Borrow vs. Sell vs. HODL</h2>
            <p>Three paths for a hypothetical dollar need over your chosen horizon. <strong>HODL</strong> doesn't fund the need at all &mdash; it preserves the most wealth, by definition. <strong>Borrow</strong> takes a loan against the stack and repays at horizon. <strong>Sell</strong> crystallizes BTC at today's price to fund the need. The HODL path quantifies the wealth cost of <em>any</em> active decision; the borrow-vs-sell comparison tells you the cheaper of the two active paths if the need is real. Future bitcoin price is the Power Law trend at end-of-horizon &mdash; central-tendency expectation, not a forecast.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bas-calc">

            <!-- ─── Shared inputs (mirror Loan Health via state sync) ─── -->
            <div class="bas-calc-inputs">
                <div class="bas-calc-field">
                    <label class="bas-calc-field-label" for="bvsBtcStack">
                        BTC stack
                        <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">The quantity of bitcoin you'd pledge as collateral. Mirrors the BTC stack input on Loan Health &mdash; change either, both update.</span></span>
                    </label>
                    <input type="number" id="bvsBtcStack" value="1.0" step="0.01" min="0" max="100000">
                    <div class="bas-calc-field-hint">Quantity of bitcoin available as collateral.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="bas-calc-field">
                    <label class="bas-calc-field-label" for="bvsBtcPrice">
                        Current BTC price (USD)
                        <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Mirrors the Current BTC price input on Loan Health. Auto-filled from the most recent monthly sample; edit to model a different starting price.</span></span>
                    </label>
                    <input type="number" id="bvsBtcPrice" value="" step="100" min="0" max="100000000">
                    <div class="bas-calc-field-hint">Auto-populated from the most recent monthly sample.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="bas-calc-field">
                    <label class="bas-calc-field-label" for="bvsLoanAmount">
                        Loan amount (USD)
                        <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">The dollar amount you'd actually need. Mirrors the Loan amount input on Loan Health &mdash; change either, both update.</span></span>
                    </label>
                    <input type="number" id="bvsLoanAmount" value="10000" step="100" min="0" max="1000000000">
                    <div class="bas-calc-field-hint">The amount you'd need either way &mdash; borrowed against the stack or netted from selling.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ─── Interest rate (shared with Loan Health) + provider presets ─── -->
            <div class="bas-calc-inputs-cost">
                <div class="bas-calc-field">
                    <div class="bas-calc-field-label bas-calc-field-label-with-display">
                        <span>
                            Interest rate (APR)
                            <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Mirrors the Interest rate input on Loan Health. Most bitcoin-backed loans are interest-only with bullet repayment &mdash; you pay interest monthly; the principal stays outstanding until you choose to repay it (or, in the borrow path here, until horizon).</span></span>
                        </span>
                        <span class="bas-calc-field-display"><span id="bvsInterestRateDisplay">10.0</span>%</span>
                    </div>
                    <input type="range" id="bvsInterestRate" min="2" max="20" value="10" step="0.5">
                    <div class="bas-calc-presets">
                        <div class="bas-calc-preset-wrap">
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-preset-bvs" data-rate="10">Tier-1 CeFi &asymp; 10%</button>
                            <span class="help-tip help-tip-preset" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Tier-1 non-rehypothecating CeFi. Sets rate to 10%. (Liquidation LTV not relevant on this tab; visit Loan Health for the full provider preset.) <a href="#question">See Question tab &rsaquo;</a></span></span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-preset-wrap">
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-preset-bvs" data-rate="14">Multisig &asymp; 14%</button>
                            <span class="help-tip help-tip-preset" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Collaborative-custody multisig. Sets rate to 14%. <a href="#question">See Question tab &rsaquo;</a></span></span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-preset-wrap">
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-preset-bvs bas-calc-preset-warning" data-rate="3">Rehypothecating &asymp; 3%</button>
                            <span class="help-tip help-tip-preset help-tip-warning" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Platforms that subsidise low headline rates by re-lending your collateral. <strong>The structural failure mode that took down Celsius, BlockFi, Genesis, and Voyager.</strong> Included to make the subsidy effect visible. <a href="#question">See Question tab &rsaquo;</a></span></span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bas-calc-field-hint">Click a preset (sets rate) or drag the slider. Liquidation LTV lives on the Loan Health tab.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ─── BvS-specific inputs (horizon / cost basis / tax rate) ─── -->
            <div class="bas-calc-bvs-section">
                <div class="bas-calc-bvs-header">
                    <h3 class="bas-calc-bvs-title">Three paths &mdash; what each leaves you with</h3>
                    <p class="bas-calc-bvs-subtitle">Borrow and sell both fund the dollar need today; HODL doesn't (you forgo the spending). <strong>HODL always preserves the most wealth at horizon</strong> &mdash; it's the mathematical reference. The verdict below quantifies what each active path <em>costs</em> in terminal wealth and identifies the cheaper of the two when the need is real.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="bas-calc-bvs-inputs">
                    <div class="bas-calc-field">
                        <div class="bas-calc-field-label bas-calc-field-label-with-display">
                            <span>
                                Time horizon
                                <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">How long until you'd repay the loan (borrow path) or how long to project forward (sell path / HODL path). All three paths are evaluated at the same future date so the comparison is apples-to-apples. Longer horizon = more time for bitcoin to appreciate.</span></span>
                            </span>
                            <span class="bas-calc-field-display"><span id="bvsHorizonDisplay">5</span> years</span>
                        </div>
                        <input type="range" id="bvsHorizon" min="1" max="15" value="5" step="1">
                    </div>

                    <div class="bas-calc-field">
                        <label class="bas-calc-field-label" for="bvsCostBasis">
                            Cost basis per BTC (USD)
                            <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">The average price per BTC at which you originally bought your stack. Used to compute capital gains tax in the sell path. Defaults to today's price (no embedded gain &mdash; the most conservative assumption for the sell path). Use the presets to model typical cycle entry points.</span></span>
                        </label>
                        <input type="number" id="bvsCostBasis" value="" step="100" min="0">
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-cb-presets">
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-bvs-cb-preset" data-cb="today">Today</button>
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-bvs-cb-preset" data-cb="2yr">2 yr ago &asymp;</button>
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-bvs-cb-preset" data-cb="4yr">4 yr ago &asymp;</button>
                            <button type="button" class="bas-calc-bvs-cb-preset" data-cb="genesis">Pre-2020 &asymp;</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="bas-calc-field">
                        <div class="bas-calc-field-label bas-calc-field-label-with-display">
                            <span>
                                Capital gains tax rate
                                <span class="help-tip" tabindex="0">?<span class="tip-content">Your effective long-term capital gains tax rate. US federal LTCG is 0%, 15%, or 20% depending on bracket; state tax may add more. Use 0% if your bitcoin is held in a tax-advantaged account (IRA, Roth, etc.).</span></span>
                            </span>
                            <span class="bas-calc-field-display"><span id="bvsCapGainsDisplay">20</span>%</span>
                        </div>
                        <input type="range" id="bvsCapGains" min="0" max="40" value="20" step="1">
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- ─── Three comparison cards ─── -->
                <!-- HODL is leftmost (the baseline / wealth-maximizing reference). -->
                <!-- Borrow and Sell follow as the two active alternatives.         -->
                <div class="bas-calc-bvs-comparison bas-calc-bvs-comparison-3col">
                    <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path bas-calc-bvs-path-hodl">
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-label">Just HODL</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-tagline">Don't borrow &middot; don't sell &middot; forgo the need</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-headline" id="basBvsHodlHeadline">&mdash; BTC</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-sublabel">retained at end of horizon</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-rows" id="basBvsHodlRows">
                            <!-- Populated by JS -->
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path bas-calc-bvs-path-borrow">
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-label">Borrow path</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-tagline">Keep the stack &middot; pay interest &middot; repay at horizon</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-headline" id="basBvsBorrowHeadline">&mdash; BTC</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-sublabel">retained at end of horizon</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-rows" id="basBvsBorrowRows">
                            <!-- Populated by JS -->
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path bas-calc-bvs-path-sell">
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-label">Sell path</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-tagline">Sell some now &middot; net loan after tax &middot; hold rest</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-headline" id="basBvsSellHeadline">&mdash; BTC</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-sublabel">retained at end of horizon</div>
                        <div class="bas-calc-bvs-path-rows" id="basBvsSellRows">
                            <!-- Populated by JS -->
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- ─── Verdict line (three-path) ─── -->
                <div class="bas-calc-bvs-verdict" id="basBvsVerdict">
                    <p>Enter a stack, current price, and loan amount above to compare the three paths.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- ─── Risk disclosure (borrow-path-scoped) ─── -->
                <!-- Liquidation risk and counterparty risk are features of   -->
                <!-- the borrow path ALONE — HODL has no lender; sell         -->
                <!-- concludes the moment the sale clears. The caveat is      -->
                <!-- explicitly scoped to borrow and styled with the green    -->
                <!-- accent so the visual ties it to the Borrow card.         -->
                <div class="bas-calc-bvs-caveat">
                    <strong>What the borrow path leaves out:</strong> the math above measures only terminal-wealth math at the Power Law trend. Borrowing also carries <a href="#loan-health">liquidation risk during drawdowns</a> (covered on Loan Health &mdash; the LTV meter and channel-position math) and <a href="#question">counterparty risk if the lender fails</a> (covered in The Question &mdash; the structural argument for verifiable, non-rehypothecating custody). Neither HODL nor selling carries these tail risks; they're features of the borrow path alone. The cheapest active path isn't automatically the right one if those risks aren't tolerable for your situation.
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- TAB IV: THE MATH — methodology and formulas -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="tab-content" id="tab-math">
        <div class="section-intro">
            <h2>The Math</h2>
            <p>The formulas the two calculators use, the data sources behind them, and what's deliberately not modelled. Held to the same standard as the math tab on the page's siblings &mdash; explicit about assumptions, transparent about gaps.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bas-math">

            <!-- ─── 1. THE POWER LAW CHANNEL ─── -->
            <div class="bas-math-section">
                <h3 class="bas-math-section-title">The Power Law channel</h3>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Every channel-position and future-price calculation on this page uses the bitcoin Power Law, originated by Giovanni Santostasi and developed into the channel framework by Matthew Me&#382;inskis at Porkopolis Economics. The trend line is:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">P(d) = 10<sup>&minus;17.668 + 5.846 &times; log<sub>10</sub>(d)</sup></div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">where <em>d</em> is days since the bitcoin genesis block (3 January 2009). The channel floor sits at <strong>0.42&times; the trend</strong>; the upper bound at <strong>3.0&times; the trend</strong>. Both have been respected across every cycle since the early years.</p>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">For derivation and historical fit, see <a href="/the-power-law.html">the Power Law page</a>.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- ─── 2. LOAN HEALTH MATH ─── -->
            <div class="bas-math-section">
                <h3 class="bas-math-section-title">Loan Health</h3>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Your current loan-to-value ratio:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">LTV = loan / (stack &times; price)</div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">The price at which your collateral is forcibly sold, given the lender's Liquidation LTV trigger:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">P<sub>liq</sub> = loan / (stack &times; liquidation_LTV)</div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Drawdown buffer &mdash; the percentage bitcoin can fall before forced sale:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">drawdown_to_liq = 1 &minus; (LTV / liquidation_LTV)</div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Annual carrying cost (interest-only model, no principal amortisation):</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">annual_interest = loan &times; rate</div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Annual cost as a fraction of stack value &mdash; the figure to compare against bitcoin's compound annual growth rate for the G &gt; R structural check:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">annual_cost_pct = annual_interest / (stack &times; price)</div>

                <p class="bas-math-prose">LTV zone classification is computed <em>relative</em> to the Liquidation LTV trigger, not as absolute bands, so a 30% LTV against an 82% threshold reads as conservative while the same 30% against a 50% threshold reads as moderate:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-table">
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row bas-math-table-header"><span>ratio = LTV / liquidation_LTV</span><span>Zone</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>ratio &lt; 0.50</span><span>Conservative</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>0.50 &le; ratio &lt; 0.80</span><span>Moderate</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>ratio &ge; 0.80</span><span>Aggressive</span></div>
                </div>

                <p class="bas-math-prose">Channel position of the liquidation price, relative to today's Power Law trend:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-table">
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row bas-math-table-header"><span>P<sub>liq</sub> / P(today)</span><span>Position</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>&lt; 0.42</span><span>Below channel floor</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>0.42 to 1.00</span><span>Between floor and trend</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>1.00 to 3.00</span><span>Above trend</span></div>
                    <div class="bas-math-table-row"><span>&ge; 3.00</span><span>Above upper bound</span></div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ─── 3. BORROW VS. SELL MATH ─── -->
            <div class="bas-math-section">
                <h3 class="bas-math-section-title">Borrow vs. Sell</h3>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">The future bitcoin price used in both paths is the Power Law trend at the end of the horizon:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">P<sub>future</sub> = P(today<sub>days</sub> + horizon_years &times; 365.25)</div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">This is a <em>central-tendency expectation</em>, not a forecast. Bitcoin can sit above or below the trend for extended periods; the comparison's directional verdict is more robust than its dollar-figure precision.</p>

                <h4 class="bas-math-subsection-title">HODL path (baseline)</h4>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">No loan, no sale, no tax, no interest:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">terminal_wealth<sub>hodl</sub> = stack &times; P<sub>future</sub></div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Mathematically always the highest of the three terminal-wealth figures &mdash; HODL sells zero BTC and pays zero interest. The HODL number is the wealth-maximising reference; the borrow and sell paths quantify what each active decision <em>costs</em> relative to it.</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">cost_vs_hodl<sub>borrow</sub> = terminal_wealth<sub>hodl</sub> &minus; terminal_wealth<sub>borrow</sub></div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">cost_vs_hodl<sub>sell</sub>   = terminal_wealth<sub>hodl</sub> &minus; terminal_wealth<sub>sell</sub></div>

                <h4 class="bas-math-subsection-title">Sell path</h4>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">To net <em>loan</em> after capital gains tax when selling at today's price:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">gain_per_BTC = max(0, price &minus; cost_basis)</div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">tax_per_BTC = gain_per_BTC &times; tax_rate</div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">net_per_BTC = price &minus; tax_per_BTC</div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">BTC<sub>sold,now</sub> = loan / net_per_BTC</div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">terminal_wealth<sub>sell</sub> = (stack &minus; BTC<sub>sold,now</sub>) &times; P<sub>future</sub></div>

                <h4 class="bas-math-subsection-title">Borrow path</h4>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Cumulative interest paid over the horizon (simple, interest-only, paid from external income rather than from the stack):</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">cumulative_interest = loan &times; rate &times; horizon_years</div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">At horizon, sell just enough BTC at P<sub>future</sub> to repay the loan principal &mdash; capital gains tax is owed on the future gain:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">gain_per_BTC<sub>future</sub> = max(0, P<sub>future</sub> &minus; cost_basis)</div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">net_per_BTC<sub>future</sub> = P<sub>future</sub> &minus; gain_per_BTC<sub>future</sub> &times; tax_rate</div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">BTC<sub>sold,horizon</sub> = loan / net_per_BTC<sub>future</sub></div>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">terminal_wealth<sub>borrow</sub> = (stack &minus; BTC<sub>sold,horizon</sub>) &times; P<sub>future</sub> &minus; cumulative_interest</div>

                <h4 class="bas-math-subsection-title">Opportunity cost (shown in each card)</h4>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">The value of BTC sold at the horizon's trend price &mdash; what those coins <em>would</em> have been worth had they been held:</p>
                <div class="bas-math-eq">opp_cost = BTC<sub>sold</sub> &times; P<sub>future</sub></div>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Dominant cost on the sell path (lots of BTC sold now). Small on the borrow path (few BTC sold at horizon to repay). The structural argument for borrowing reduces to: <em>does the opportunity cost of the BTC you'd sell exceed the cumulative interest of carrying the loan?</em></p>
            </div>

            <!-- ─── 4. WHAT'S NOT MODELLED ─── -->
            <div class="bas-math-section">
                <h3 class="bas-math-section-title">What's not modelled</h3>
                <p class="bas-math-prose">Several real-world dimensions are deliberately out of scope to keep the page readable. Each is logged for follow-up:</p>
                <ul class="bas-math-list">
                    <li><strong>Variable interest rates.</strong> Rate is held constant across the horizon. Real CeFi loan rates can shift with macro conditions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Margin call windows.</strong> Many platforms post a margin call before forced sale, giving the borrower a chance to top up collateral. The calculator assumes a clean trigger at the Liquidation LTV.</li>
                    <li><strong>DCA accumulation.</strong> The stack is held constant. Continued accumulation over the horizon would improve both paths' outcomes.</li>
                    <li><strong>Loan refinancing / perpetual leverage.</strong> The borrow path assumes a single repayment at horizon. The strategic case (never repay; refinance forward indefinitely) is on the roadmap.</li>
                    <li><strong>Counterparty default.</strong> Celsius / BlockFi / Genesis / Voyager-style failure not modelled. Recovery distributions by archetype are on the roadmap.</li>
                    <li><strong>DeFi infrastructure exploits.</strong> Oracle stale, bridge depeg, wrapping risks are not modelled. Loss in those scenarios is typically the full collateral with near-zero recovery; that's a separate roadmap item.</li>
                    <li><strong>Tax detail beyond federal LTCG.</strong> Only US-style federal long-term capital gains modelled. State, city, foreign-jurisdiction tax not included. Short-term gains (holding period &lt;1 year) not modelled &mdash; if the stack is recent, the actual tax burden on the sell path will be higher than shown.</li>
                    <li><strong>Multi-cycle path dependency.</strong> The horizon's endpoint is the Power Law trend regardless of what bitcoin does in between. The 100-BTC-at-$100 thought experiment from the Question tab is a useful corrective: the structural argument doesn't depend on smooth appreciation.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>

